elements.content: The syntheses, structures, and magnetic properties of a series of di- and trivalent hydridotris(3,5-dimethylpyrazol-1-yl)borate (Tp*) cyanomanganates are described. Treatment of tris(acetylacetonate)manganese(III) [Mn(acac)3] with KTp* and tetra(ethyl)ammonium cyanide affords [NEt4][(Tp*)MnII(κ2-acac)(CN)] (1), as the first monocyanomanganate(II) complex; attempted oxidation of 1 with iodine affords {(Tp*)MnII(κ2-acac3-CN)} n (2) as a one-dimensional chain and bimetallic {[NEt4][(Tp*)MnII(κ2-acac3-CN)]2(μ-CN) (3) as the major and minor products, respectively. A fourth complex, [NEt4][(Tp*)MnII(η2-acac3-CN)(η1-NC-acac)] (4), is obtained via treatment of Mn(acac3-CN)3 with KTp* and [NEt4]CN, while [NEt4]2[MnII(CN)4] (5) was prepared from manganese(II) trifluoromethanesulfonate and excess [NEt4]CN. Tricyanomanganate(III) complexes, [cat][(Tp*)MnIII(CN)3] [cat = NEt4 +, 7; PPN+, 8], are prepared via sequential treatment of Mn(acac3-CN)3 with KTp*, followed by [NEt4]CN, or [cat]3[MnIII(CN)6] with (Tp*)SnBu2Cl. Magnetic measurements indicate that 1, 2, and 4 contain isotropic MnII (S = 5/2; g = 2.00) centers, and no long-range magnetic ordering is found above 1.8 K. Compounds 7 and 8 contain S = 1 MnIII centers that adopt singly degenerate spin ground states without orbital contributions to their magnetic moments.

elements.content: Recent studies indicate that polynuclear cyanometalate complexes that contain paramagnetic centers with first-order spin−orbit coupling exhibit fundamentally different behavior than oxide-bridged complexes, in which the spin−orbit effect is nearly quenched by the low-symmetry ligand environment. In polynuclear cyanometalate complexes containing [M n (CN)6]m− and [(L)M n (CN)3] m− (M n = ReII, MoIII, FeIII, MnIII, etc.) ions, where L is a facially coordinated tridentate ligand, significant orbital contributions to their spin ground states are exhibited that are a necessary factor for establishing uniaxial type anisotropy and an activation energy barrier (Δ) to thermal magnetization reversal, i.e. Single-Molecule Magnet (SMM) behavior. The tripodal ligands limit the numbers and spatial arrangement of cyanide linkages formed, and via judicious choice of cyanometalate building blocks, a variety of polynuclear complexes and, in some cases, magnetic chains that exhibit slow relaxation of the magnetization may be systematically engineered. Among these derivatives, several are reported to exhibit spin crossover, superparamagnetism and optically responsive behavior. While tuning the single-ion anisotropy can in principle be accomplished via alterations of metal ions, spin state and/or orbital anisotropy in various building blocks, predicting how these single-ion properties impact overall magnetic anisotropy of the polynuclear complexes, still remains a persistent challenge. However, the orbital contributions are often sensitive to local crystal fields, and this feature offers the prospect of tuning magnetic properties at the single-ion level via distortion of the metal ion coordination spheres.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

Recent studies indicate that polynuclear cyanometalate complexes that contain paramagnetic centers with first-order spin-orbit coupling exhibit fundamentally different behavior than oxide-bridged complexes, in which the spin-orbit effect is nearly quenched by the low-symmetry ligand environment. In polynuclear cyanometalate complexes containing [M n (CN)6]m- and [(L)M n (CN)3] m- (M n  = ReII, MoIII, FeIII, MnIII, etc.) ions, where L is a facially coordinated tridentate ligand, significant orbital contributions to their spin ground states are exhibited that are a necessary factor for establishing uniaxial type anisotropy and an activation energy barrier (Δ) to thermal magnetization reversal, i.e. Single-Molecule Magnet (SMM) behavior. The tripodal ligands limit the numbers and spatial arrangement of cyanide linkages formed, and via judicious choice of cyanometalate building blocks, a variety of polynuclear complexes and, in some cases, magnetic chains that exhibit slow relaxation of the magnetization may be systematically engineered. Among these derivatives, several are reported to exhibit spin crossover, superparamagnetism and optically responsive behavior. While tuning the single-ion anisotropy can in principle be accomplished via alterations of metal ions, spin state and/or orbital anisotropy in various building blocks, predicting how these single-ion properties impact overall magnetic anisotropy of the polynuclear complexes, still remains a persistent challenge. However, the orbital contributions are often sensitive to local crystal fields, and this feature offers the prospect of tuning magnetic properties at the single-ion level via distortion of the metal ion coordination spheres.

elements.content: High-spin MnIII (S = 2) ions are the most common paramagnetic ions used in the construction of oxo-carboxylate SMMs and are the principal source of their single-ion anisotropy. However, in cyanometalate chemistry, only materials containing low-spin [MnII(CN)6]4− (S = 1/2) and [MnIII(CN)6]3− (S = 1) anions have been reported prior to our work. These cyanometalate anions exhibit first-order orbital contributions to their degenerate spin ground states and are known to efficiently engage in π back bonding and cyanide-mediated superexchange interactions within Mn(μ-CN)M′ units; of these, only [MnIII(CN)6]3− has been used to construct discrete polynuclear complexes.

elements.content: Prior to 2010, there were six known paramagnetic cyanomanganates: K4[MnII(CN)6]·3H2O, Na4[MnII(CN)6]·10H2O, K3[MnIII(CN)6]·H2O, [PPN]3[MnIII(CN)6], [PPN]2[MnIV(CN)4], and [PPN]2[MnII(CN)4]. The low-spin di- and trivalent hexacyanomanganates are known to exhibit low-spin t 2g 5 (S = 1/2, g = 2.5) and t 2g 4 (S = 1, g = 2.47) electron configurations, respectively, with significant orbital contributions to their magnetic moments found, while tetracyanomanganate(II) complexes are magnetically isotropic (S = 5/2, 6 A 1 ground state). A single pentanuclear complex, [MnII(tmphen)]3[MnIII(CN)6]2 (tmphen =3,4,7,8-tetramethyl-1,10-phenanthroline), is reported to exhibit slow relaxation of its magnetization below 1.8 K.

elements.content: Over the past several years, we have strived to engineer structurally related polynuclear complexes containing paramagnetic [(TpR)M n (CN) m ] n−m−1 ions, where TpR is a pyrazolyborate anion. We have extensively utilized these di- and tricyano pyrazolylborate complexes to prepare a variety of tri-, tetra-, and octanuclear derivatives that exhibit SMM properties. In these polynuclear complexes, we discovered that substitution at the [(TpR)M n (CN) m ] n−m−1 sites [M n = VO2+, CrIII, FeIII, CoIII] appears to be the most efficient means to tune the magnetic and optical properties. Among known analogues, polynuclear {FeCo} n (n = 2, 4) complexes are found to exhibit thermally- and light-induced changes in their optical and magnetic properties with exceptionally long lifetimes (up to 10 y at 120 K).

We reasoned that insertion of tricyanomanganate(III) ions into the trivalent sites of rectangular {MIII 2MII 2} and octanuclear {MIII 4MII 4} complexes might allow for systematic investigations into how orbital symmetry, magnetic, and optical properties change upon MIII ion substitution in structurally related complexes.

elements.content: Unfortunately, we have been unable to find a single pyrazolylborate complex that is suitable for the preparation of any paramagnetic cyanomangante until only recently. However, given the number of known manganese β-diketonates, we turned our attention toward these reagents and investigated their usefulness for preparing [(Tp*)Mn n (CN)3] n−4 complexes. Substituted complexes of Mn(acacR)3 (acacR = acetylacetonate, dipivaloylmethanoate, 3-cyanoacetylacetonate, etc.) stoichiometry are attractive starting materials because they are generally air and water stable soluble in a variety of organic solvents and their redox potentials can be systematically altered via introduction of various functional groups. We reasoned that sequential substitution of acetylacetonates with pyrazolylborate anions followed by cyanide would minimize the formation of [(Tp*)2Mn n ] n−2 and [Mn n (CN) m ] n−m complexes and likely afford the desired tricyanomanganates. Herein, we describe the synthesis, crystallographic and magnetic characterization of several β-diketonates and their transformation into cyanomanganates.

Experimental Section

Materials

All operations were conducted under an argon atmosphere using standard Schlenk and drybox techniques. Transfers of solutions containing cyanide were carried out through stainless steel cannulas. Solvents were distilled under dinitrogen from CaH2 (acetonitrile, dichloromethane), sodium-benzophenone (diethyl ether), or magnesium turnings (methanol) and sparged with argon prior to use. The preparation of KTp*, (Tp*)SnBu2Cl, K3[Mn(CN)6]⋅H2O, [NEt4]CN, 3-cyano-2,4-pentanedione (Hacac3-CN), tris(dipivaloylmethanato)manganese(III), MnIII(acac)3, [MnIII(acac3-CN)3], Mn(OTf)2, and {[cis-MII(bipy)2(OH2)2][OTf]2}⋅3H2O (MII = Co, Ni) are described elsewhere. Iodine (Baker), cobaltacene (Aldrich), and 2,2'-bipyridine (Aldrich) were used as received.

elements.content: Realizing that the manganese centers are reduced during the above reactions (likely by cyanide), we investigated the reactivity of several substituted Mn(acacR)3 complexes with KTp*. Treatment of Mn(acacR)3 (acacR = 3-cyano-2,4-pentanedionato, acac3-CN) with methanolic KTp*, followed by [NEt4]CN, affords [NEt4][(Tp*)MnII(κ2-acac3-CN)(η1-NC-acac)]·MeCN·1/2Et2O (4) as the major product. Subsequent treatment of 4 in methanol with excess [NEt4]CN affords [NEt4][(Tp*)MnIII(CN)3] (7) in moderate yield; efforts to isolate the putative divalent tricyano intermediate have been unsuccessful to date. In an attempt to simplify the preparation of 7, we reasoned that if pyrazolylborate stannyl reagents [e.g., (Tp*)SnBu2Cl] can effectively substitute coordinated halides for Tp* anions, then pseudohalide complexes (such as cyanometalates) should undergo analogous transformations. Indeed, treatment of [cat]3[MnIII(CN)6] with (Tp*)SnBu2Cl in dichloromethane affords [cat][(Tp*)MnIII(CN)3] complexes (7, NEt4 +; 8, PPN+, bis(triphenyl)phosphine iminium) in modest crystalline yields.

elements.content: While investigating the cyanide substitution chemistry of manganese complexes, we also discovered an improved and direct method for the preparation of a homoleptic tetracyanomanganate(II) complex. elements.content: Attempted insertion of 7 and 8 into the trivalent sites of {MnIII 2MII 2} square complexes (MII = Mn, Co, Ni) at room temperature were met with limited success due to redox and cyanide redistribution reactions. Unfortunately, all attempts to obtain structural data of the putative cyanide-bridged polynuclear tetracyanonickelate have been unsuccessful.

elements.content: Reasoning that ligand substitution and redistribution would proceed more slowly at lower reaction temperatures (−40 °C), we reinvestigated the reaction chemistry of 7 with anhydrous divalent triflates and 2,2′-bipyridine mixtures. Indeed treatment of 7 with manganese(II) and nickel(II) trifluoromethanesulfonates in the presence of 2,2′-bipyridine affords tetranuclear complexes of {[(Tp*)MnIII(CN)3]2[MII(bpy)2]2[OTf]2}·2DMF stoichiometry (MII = Mn, Ni). Surprisingly, analogous efforts to prepare {MnIII 2CoII 2} complexes consistently met with failure. For example, treatment of 7 with [cis-CoII(bpy)2(OH2)2][OTf]2 at or below room temperature cleanly affords [cis-CoIII(CN)2(bpy)2][OTf]·MeCN (10; ν̅CN = 2142 cm−1) as the sole cyanide-containing complex, while [(Tp*)2MnII] is the only isolable pyrazolylborate complex. Similarly, treatment of 7 with CoII(OTf)2 and two equivalents of 2,2′-bipyridine affords a mixture of reaction products regardless of reaction temperature. From these studies, we infer that facile cyanide redistribution and electron transfer prevents the formation of the desired {MnIII 2CoII 2} complex.

elements.content: Crystals of 7 and 8 are found in the trigonal (P32) and triclinic (P1̅) space groups, respectively (Table ). The six-coordinate tricyano anions adopt nearly ideal C 3v symmetry and exhibit markedly different Mn−C and Mn−N bond lengths in comparison to divalent analogues (Figure S2, ). Assuming that the Mn−CCN distances scale as a function of the metal center oxidation state, MnIII centers are expected to engage in stronger electrostatic interactions with coordinated cyanides, and the shortest Mn−C distances should be seen for 7 and 8. Conversely, efficient π backbonding (if present) should afford the short Mn−CCN distances in divalent complexes. Consistent with this assumption, the Mn−CCN bonds in 7 and 8 are rather short, ranging from 1.976(3) Å [for 7] to 1.982(3) Å [for 8], and are also considerably shorter (Table ) than those in structures of 1 and 5. The Mn−C distances are similar to those seen in 9 [1.986(1) Å] and [PPN]3[MnIII(CN)6] [2.0020(2) Å], confirming that trivalent manganese centers are present. Considering the infrared and structural data, we conclude that little π-back bonding occurs in any of the prepared mono- and tricyanomanganate complexes [1, 7, and 8].

elements.content: Given that trivalent centers are expected to have smaller ionic radii than divalent ones, tighter binding of the MnIII ions within the [N]3 pocket of the facially coordinate Tp* ligand is anticipated. The Mn1 distance from the mean [N]3 plane of the three coordinated Tp* nitrogen atoms appear to support this assumption: the Mn1−[N]3 distances are 1.476(2), 1.377(2), 1.432(3) and 1.453(3), 1.403(2), 1.193(3), and 1.205(2) Å for 1−4, 7, and 8, respectively, with the smallest values being found for 7 and 8 (Table ). Consistent with periodic trends, the average Mn−C distances in 7 and 8 [1.985(3) and 1.983(3) Å] are also shorter than those seen for early transition metal [(Tp*)MIII(CN)3]− anions [e.g., TiIII, 2.171(3) Å; VIIII, 2.090(3) Å] and are longer than those observed when CoIII is present [1.875(3) Å] (Table ). The N−Mn−N bond angles are also more acute in 7 and 8, ranging from 89.4(1) to 90.3(1)°, while the C−Mn−C angles are between 85.8(1) and 91.7(1)°, suggesting that the Tp* ligand exerts modest steric pressure on the cyanide ligands in 7 and 8 (vide infra, Table ).

elements.content: Consistent with previously described infrared and structural data, the magnetic measurements suggest that 7 is an authentic tricyanomanganate(III) complex. The room temperature χT value [1.1 cm3 K mol−1] of 7 is close to the value expected for a complex containing MnIII ions (S = 1). In comparison, values reported for either [PPN]2[MnII(CN)4] or [PPN]3[MnIII(CN)6] (4.49 and 1.98 cm3 K mol−1) are much higher, which suggests that trivalent ions are present and that orbital contributions to the spin ground state are nearly absent in 7. The temperature dependence of the χT data follows Curie behavior down to ca. 100 K and then decreases further toward a minimum of 0.15 cm3 K mol−1 at 1.8 K. An anisotropic Heisenberg Hamiltonian (H = DS Mn 2) can be used to fit the experimental data, and g and D/k B parameters of 2.09(2) and +9.4(2) K are found, respectively. The unexpectedly large D parameter is probably due to antiferromagnetic intercomplex interactions, and this assumption is supported by the M vs H data collected below 8 K, in that the same D value is not reproduced when using an anisotropic Heisenberg model. Additionally, compound 7 remains EPR silent down to 2 K and consistent with behavior expected for complexes containing an integer spin ion.

elements.content: Further evidence in support of an S = 1 ground state for 7 can be found in extended Hückel tight-binding (EHTB) calculations. Conclusions

Manganese pyrazolylboates are easily prepared from substituted 2,4-pentanediones under mild reaction conditions. These complexes exhibit rich reactivity under oxidative and metathesis reaction conditions and can be used to prepare new paramagnetic mono- and tricyanomanganate complexes. The divalent complexes exhibit isotropic S = 5/2 spin ground states, while the corresponding C 3v -symmetric tricyanomanganate(III) complexes adopt a S = 1 spin states. These results highlight the role that symmetry and orbital degeneracy play in introducing orbital angular momentum contributions to the magnetic ground state of structurally related tricyanometalate anions.
